{
  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustic devices to reduce human-wildlife conflict at aquaculture systems compare to their use on fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "At aquaculture systems, six studies were identified: four of six (including five before-and-after and/or site comparison studies and one controlled study) found reduced predation on caged salmon by grey seals, harbour seals and South American sea lions, or fewer harbour seals approaching a fish cage; two studies found no reduction in harbour seal predation at salmon farms or in the presence, approach distances, group sizes or time spent around fin-fish farms by common bottlenose dolphins [2775]. On fishing gear, thirty-three studies were identified. Behaviour: twelve of 16 controlled studies (including three replicated) reported reduced approaches, encounters or interactions with nets/lines, or reduced activity/sightings by harbour porpoises, common bottlenose dolphins, tucuxi dolphins, finless porpoises and seals; four studies found no significant behavioural effect on common bottlenose dolphins, harbour porpoises, Indo-Pacific humpback dolphins or dugongs. Entanglement/unwanted catch: nine studies (including seven controlled and two before-and-after) found fewer collisions or entanglements of humpback whales, harbour porpoises, Franciscana dolphins, beaked whales and small cetaceans; three studies found reductions for some species but not others; one controlled study found fewer harbour porpoise entanglements only with a \u2018complete\u2019 set of devices; one replicated, controlled study found reductions in one fishing area but not another. Human-wildlife conflict: five of six controlled studies (one replicated) found reduced damage to fish catches and/or nets by common bottlenose dolphins and seals, while one study found no reduction in swordfish catch damage by California sea lions [2808].",
